{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:13:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.12,0.18,0.71,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72509"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24598"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72509"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGas exchange in the lungs follows physical principles that govern how gases dissolve in liquids. This process is essential for maintaining adequate oxygen delivery to tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes Henry\u0027s law regarding gases dissolved in liquids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The amount of dissolved gas is independent of pressure","The amount of dissolved gas increases exponentially with pressure","The amount of dissolved gas is inversely proportional to its partial pressure","The amount of dissolved gas is directly proportional to its partial pressure","The amount of dissolved gas depends only on temperature"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe amount of dissolved gas being directly proportional to its partial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct statement of Henry\u0027s law. This fundamental principle explains how oxygen dissolves in blood plasma according to its partial pressure in the alveoli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe amount of dissolved gas is independent of pressure\u003C/strong\u003E: the amount of dissolved gas changes in direct relation to pressure changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe amount of dissolved gas increases exponentially with pressure\u003C/strong\u003E: the relationship between dissolved gas and pressure is linear, not exponential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe amount of dissolved gas is inversely proportional to its partial pressure\u003C/strong\u003E: as partial pressure increases, the amount of dissolved gas increases, not decreases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe amount of dissolved gas depends only on temperature\u003C/strong\u003E: while temperature affects solubility, the primary determinant is partial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHenry\u0027s law is particularly important in understanding respiratory physiology, as it governs the dissolution of respiratory gases in blood and helps explain conditions like decompression sickness in diving.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Henry\u0027s law states that the amount of dissolved gas in a liquid is directly proportional to its partial pressure above the liquid.","This principle explains gas exchange in the lungs, where oxygen dissolves in blood according to its partial pressure in alveoli.","Temperature affects gas solubility - gases become less soluble as temperature increases."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57979"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T22:03:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T22:04:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72509"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null